</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="type locality">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Type locality.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Germany, Eifel, Totenmaar, 22.2.1974.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Valvae dorsiventral, dorsal margin broadly convex, ventral margin straight; ends not protracted, rounded, or subrostrate to rostrate; length 21.5-41.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, breadth 8.0-11.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, L/B ratio 2.7-4.0; axial area narrow, linear-arched, indistinct central area; striae 9-13 in 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, becoming 11-14 toward ends, one isolated pore at end of central striae on ventral side; 22-27 punctae in 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The combination of 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Krammer" authorityYear="2002" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Cymbellaceae" genus="Cymbella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cymbella excisa subsp. var. var. procera" order="Cymbellales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="excisa" subSpecies="var." variety="procera">Cymbella excisa var. procera</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Kuetz" authorityYear="1844" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Cymbellaceae" genus="Cymbella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cymbella affinis" order="Cymbellales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cymbella affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would be illegitimate unless it was given a new name, because it would be a later homonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="Krammer" authorityYear="2002" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Cymbellaceae" genus="Cymbella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cymbella affinis subsp. var. var. procera" order="Cymbellales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="affinis" subSpecies="var." variety="procera">Cymbella affinis var. procera</taxonomicName>
Krammer. Specimens designated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K" journalOrPublisher="Diatoms of Europe" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 584" refId="B7" refString="Krammer, K, 2002. Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella. Diatoms of Europe 3: 1 - 584" title="Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella." volume="3" year="2002">Krammer (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, i.e., the preparation 212A IOK (BRM), were found to belong to more than one taxon therefore to clarify the taxonomy we designated a lectotype as established in Art. 9.11 of the ICN (
<bibRefCitation author="McNeill, J" journalOrPublisher="Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 240" refId="B14" refString="McNeill, J, Barrie, FR, Buck, WR, Demoulin, V, Greuter, W, Hawksworth, DL, Herendeen, PS, Knapp, S, Marhold, K, Prado, J, Prud'Homme Van Reine, WF, Smith, GF, Wiersema, JH, Turland, NJ, 2012. International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code) adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Koeltz Scientific Books, Koenigstein: 1 - 240" title="International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code) adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011" year="2012">McNeill et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
A broader range of metric characteristics were highlighted in this study compared to the characterization of the type population (
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K" journalOrPublisher="Diatoms of Europe" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 584" refId="B7" refString="Krammer, K, 2002. Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella. Diatoms of Europe 3: 1 - 584" title="Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella." volume="3" year="2002">Krammer 2002</bibRefCitation>
, p. 28). We find smaller (21.5-41.0 vs. 24-41 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) and narrower (8.0-11.0 vs. 8.4-11.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) representatives of this taxon compared to the 
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K" journalOrPublisher="Diatoms of Europe" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 584" refId="B7" refString="Krammer, K, 2002. Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella. Diatoms of Europe 3: 1 - 584" title="Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella." volume="3" year="2002">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Krammer’s">Krammer's</normalizedToken>
(2002)
</bibRefCitation>
records. Still considering 
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K" journalOrPublisher="Diatoms of Europe" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" pagination="1 - 584" refId="B7" refString="Krammer, K, 2002. Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella. Diatoms of Europe 3: 1 - 584" title="Diatoms of the European inland waters and comparable habitats. Cymbella." volume="3" year="2002">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Krammer’s">Krammer's</normalizedToken>
(2002)
</bibRefCitation>
findings, we observe more densely striated (9-13 vs. 9-11 striae in 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) and less punctate (22-27 vs. 24-27 punctae in 10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) valves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
